when roll out a deployment, it creates replicasets 
to deploy to a new version:
option 1:
in deployment-definition file, update the version number at spec.template.spec.containers.image
$ k apply -f deployment.definition.yml

option 2:
$ k set image deployment/myapp=deployment nginx=nginx:1.9.1


two different StrategyTyle:
Recreate    //shut down all the environments which have the old version, and deploy the new version to all the environments, it would have a short outrage
RollingUpdate    //default

there are more deployment strategy:
Blue/green
Canary: roll out a new version of a small trafic and test, if test passes, roll out new version to all the replicasets; important in production
it's implemented by setting selector in service-definition file, as well as same label types in myapp-primary.yaml and myapp-canary.yaml


Blue/green    //deploy to both environments, starting with a low traffic to the new site, and as time goes, putting more and more traffic to the new environment until the old environment shuts

status:
$ k rollout status deployment/myapp-deployment
$ k rollout history deployment/myapp-deployment

rollback a deployment:
$ k rollout undo deployment myapp-deployment
verify:
$ k get replicasets


steps of performing deployments:
create
rollout
verify: rollout history


update an image in a deployment:
option 1:
kubectl set image deploy frontend simple-webapp=kodekloud/webapp-color:v2  
//this route might be found in this way: run k describe deployment, get the information as below, then udpate the image to kodekloud/webapp-color:v2 
Pod Template:
  Labels:  name=webapp
  Containers:
   simple-webapp:    //container name
    Image:         kodekloud/webapp-color:v1

option 2:
kubectl edit deployment frontend    //no need other commands following it

